annotations: So don’t try this at home

Throughout the song, Reneé references memories of her and an ex-partner in different rooms of the home such as the living room or the eponymous kitchen. Taken literally, this could be seen as a warning to not allow someone to enmesh themselves so completely into one’s life and home to the point where everything is a reminder of a past heartbreak.

“Don’t try this at home” is a common phrase used by people attempting something risky or dangerous towards their audience. It can be used both in jest or as a serious disclaimer to avoid legal issues. As a result of this heartbreak, she reached the conclusion that falling in love is a dangerous choice worthy of a warning.

The couch that we sat on back in New York
 Has made its way, three thousand miles to LA

Reneé famously made her Broadway debut playing Regina George in “Mean Girls” from June 7th, 2019 to its closure due to the COVID-19 pandemic in March 11, 2020.



She currently stars as Leighton in the HBO show, “Sex Lives of College Girls”, which began production in November 2020 in LA.
’Cause it’s real once everyone knows

Here, Renee is likely referring to how social media impacts modern-day relationships and breakups. She and her significant other had posts on social media sites and oftentimes, deleting posts of your significant other signals to everyone that the relationship is over. Renee realizes that once she deletes her videos of this person from her social media accounts, everyone will know that they are over and it will solidify that the relationship is over, thus she is scared to do so. This line also speaks to what it’s like to live in the public eye and have a relationship with someone when people are invested in your relationship.
But I’m too scared to delete all our videos
Reneé and the person this song is about were most known in the theater community for covering showtunes that weren’t from their respective shows

annotations: [Chorus]

This chorus is different because it switches the perspective. Here, Renee is speculating that she doesn’t actually want to get better and wants to stay where she is. She says she’ll hate Colorado because then she’d like herself and work on her mental health, suggesting that maybe she doesn’t actually want to do those things and would rather stay in her self-destructive ways.
I think my life might be better if I lived in Colorado (Hmm)

Reneé revealed in an interview with Variety that she has a special connection with the state of Colorado. Growing up her family would embark on annual ski vacations there, and it was there where she first fell in love with music.

Who am I kiddin’, I’m addicted to the chip on my shoulder (Hmm)
 I like it best breakin’ a sweat, so why go somewhere that is colder

In an interview with Rolling Stone, Reneé reveals that she is super proud of these lyrics:

In “Colorado,” I sing “I’m addicted to the chip on my shoulder.” “Colorado” is special to me because the writing is so concise. The lyrics are everything to me: “I like it best breaking a sweat. So I go somewhere where it’s colder.” It’s a song about being addicted to the grind. Like I’ll complain about being, like, “Jesus fucking Christ. I’m so burned out and I’m so tired.” But I’m like, “I love that feeling,” which is probably something I need to work on.

description.plain:
“What Can I Do” is the fifth track on Reneé Rapp’s debut EP. In an interview with Rolling Stone Reneé revealed that:

“What Can I Do” is the first openly gay song that I ever wrote. Though I’ve been out for many, many years, I never ever wrote songs about my queer relationships. I only wrote them about my hetero relationships. And it was wild because I really wanted to; I just didn’t know how. I honestly think, looking back, that’s a touch of internalized homophobia … For me, that song is so important because it is the first queer song that I wrote that I was really proud of. And as somebody who’s bisexual, I think a lot of times it’s very easy for me to just exist in queerness as a bisexual person who only speaks on the hetero parts of my life. That song made me feel so good about the really colorful and gay parts of my life.

translation_songs.title: Reneé Rapp - ​What Can I Do (Traducción al Español)

annotations:
Are, are you?
 Are, are you?

This is a subverted rhyme, following the AABB rhyme scheme. Throughout the song, she seems to be battling with unrequited love, picking petals off a flower. Deliberately omitting the last rhyme implies the words left unspoken – Are, are you (gay)?

The incomplete question hangs in the air for a while then fades off, as if she chose to give up her what ifs for friendship, loving her from a distance instead.

Your boyfriend’s in the bathroom and I’m holdin’ your hand
 I wonder if he notices the things that I can
 You don’t even get it, no, you don’t understand
 I want you, but I know I’m only one of your friends
 I know all about you, all your favorite things
 I listen to your stories, all your wildest dreams
 And you go on for hours, say he’s not what you need
 You know you’re too good for him, but if it were me

In an interview with Rolling Stone, Reneé reveals the inspiration behind the song:

When I wrote “What Can I Do,” it was just about really, really, really falling super hard for a close friend of mine who is straight, but every now and again flirts with me and was in a relationship that was so not suited for her.
And so it was just me enviously and innocently watching her go through this relationship and not be treated properly. And selfishly, I was like, “I literally love you. I would never want you to feel like that.” It’s really just this feeling of yearning for somebody where you don’t know if you’re just friends or not.

In the same interview Reneé goes on to explain the use of gendered terms in her songs:

It’s interesting too because I didn’t really realize necessarily why, but I was always so against using any sort of gendered term or pronoun in any of my songs. Even though I’m writing about these specific relationships, whether they be with men, women, or just a person, as somebody who likes everyone, I wanted to be able to fit the song with whatever…So when it comes to using gendered terms, I only want to do it in a way that feels authentic and right. “What Can I Do” was a place that felt really authentic for it to reference that “your boyfriend is in the bathroom.” But it still leaves the other person’s gender or sexual identity completely up in the air. Which I really like. But obviously, I’m going to talk about it.

annotations:
I don’t miss you
 ’Til the moment when I flip off the lights and I’m in this room
 Going back in space and time when we’re still kissin’

Reneé laments about how certain rooms bring her right back to moments she has shared with this person, a sentiment also explored in “In the Kitchen:

When I walk in the kitchen, my heart hits the floor
‘Cause it’s you that I’m missin’, I still see a vision of us cookin' dinner
And you holding me from behind (From behind)
I’m just talkin’ with your ghost and dancin’ with your demons

Reneé explores a similar idea in “In the Kitchen”:

So I’ll dance with your ghost in the living room
